canonical:
  title: 禮部郞中宋就讓起復不允批答
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 云云據禮經而欲畢通喪雖人子愼終之義迫王事而權從吉制亦朝臣順變之宜盖由古而行之非自今而始者汝頃遭憂釁深軫哀傷一心猶矢於終天百日已周於過隙合循成例復卽舊官何遽陳牢讓之辭而欲避已行之命義不孤慈母之惠孝則可謂無虧業已爲寡人之臣忠亦似難偏廢毋堅一執以遂兩全云云
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 禮部郞中宋就讓起復不允批答
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 云云。據禮經而欲畢通喪。雖人子愼終之義。迫王事而權從吉制。亦朝臣順變之宜。盖由古而行之。非自今而始者。汝頃遭憂釁。深軫哀傷。一心猶矢於終天。百日已周於過隙。合循成例。復卽舊官。何遽陳牢讓之辭。而欲避已行之命。義不孤慈母之惠。孝則可謂無虧。業已爲寡人之臣。忠亦似難偏廢。毋堅一執。以遂兩全云云。
korean:
  title: 예부낭중 송취 양 기복 불윤 비답
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 운운.예경(禮經)에 의거하여 3년상을 마치려 함은 비록 아들된 자의 마지막을 삼가는 의리이나, 왕사(王事)에 부득이하여 특례로 상복을 벗는 것도 또한 신하로서 권도(權道)를 좇는 길이다. 이는 대개 예로부터 행하여 온 일이요, 오늘날에 시작된 것이 아니다.그대가 저번에 친상(親喪)을 만나 몹시 슬퍼하면서 평생토록 애통 속에서 지내기를 맹세했다. 그러나 백 일이 어느덧 지났으니, 전례에 따라 옛 관직에 다시 나아가는 것이 마땅하다. 그런데 어찌 문득 굳이 사양하는 글을 올려 이미 내려진 명을 피하려 하는가. 자모(慈母)의 은혜를 저버리지 않으려 하니 그 효성은 지극하다 할 것이나, 이미 과인의 신하가 되었으니 충성도 또한 폐하기 어려운 것이다. 한결같이 고집만 피우지 말고 충(忠)과 효(孝) 양쪽을 다 온전히 하는 도리를 이루도록 하라.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0330_010_0080&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Royal Response Declining Song Ji's Request for Extended Mourning
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    ...According to the rites of antiquity, to complete the full three years of mourning is indeed the sacred duty of a filial son who honors his parents in death. Yet when the needs of the realm demand it, to lay aside mourning robes by royal exception is equally the wisdom of a loyal minister who adapts to circumstance. This practice, I assure you, descends from ancient times and is no invention of our present age.

    You recently endured the loss of your parent and have grieved deeply, swearing an oath to dwell in sorrow all your days. And yet a hundred days have already passed like a fleeting shadow. It is proper that you should follow precedent and return to your former office. Why then do you suddenly send words of stubborn refusal, seeking to evade a command already given? Your desire to honor the kindness of your mother is admirable, and your filial piety cannot be called incomplete. But you have become my servant, and from this loyalty too you cannot withdraw. Do not cling so rigidly to one path alone. Rather, seek the way that honors both duty and devotion, that both may stand complete.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Song Ji (宋就) was a Song Dynasty official whose request for extended mourning after his parent's death was denied by the royal court, likely during the Goryeo period when this response was written.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'hundred days' refers to a traditional period of initial mourning observance in East Asian practice.
  - key: ''
    value: The tension between 'filial piety' (孝) and 'loyalty' (忠)—the two cardinal virtues of Confucian ethics—forms the philosophical heart of this royal admonition.
